Guo Chuwang made this composition. The idea is that the wild geese are flying high on their wings, and that the long sky is a southern expedition, in order to imply a sense of open-mindedness and high ambition. The melody is mellow and majestic, and the rhythm is undulating. This piece uses the metaphor of the flying autumn geese as a metaphor to express the feelings of those who are not met with talent and pretend to be noble.

Name.ValueInfo: <color=#FF9A00FF> The Pheasant Flies in the Morning" </color>

ItemDescription.Value: It is said to have been composed by a scholar of the State of Qi during the Warring States period. He was old and had no wife, so when he saw the pheasants flying together, he was touched by the scene and sighed about his misfortunes, so he put his love in the silk tung.

Name.ValueInfo: <color=#FF9A00FF> Autumn Thoughts on the Blue Sky </color>

ItemDescription.Value: By Cai Yong. It is a distant and harmonious composition, which makes one's spirit clear and tranquil and transcends the human realm.

Guo Xin often sailed at the merging of the two waters of Xia and Xiang. Whenever he looked at Jiuyi Mountain, which was covered by clouds and water, and saw the sight of the rushing clouds and water, he felt the infinite emotion of the fragmentation of the mountains and rivers and the drift of the times and composed this song to send his feelings of longing.

This piece depicts the story of "Nie Zheng Stabbing King Han". It is the only piece of music with the atmosphere of fighting and fighting with spears, and the whole piece is full of indignant and unyielding spirit.

ItemDescription.Value: Tieke zither, Fengsei style, black lacquer, antlers and gray tires, gold emblem, ancient pine wood, slightly curved face and base, broad shoulders and tail, ancient and thick tone.
The lacquer color is black with red. On the back, above the dragon pond is engraved with "Xiao Yue".

Tang Dynasty guqin. It is in the "moon" style, but the full moon is not on the shoulders but on the wings at the fifth or sixth emblem, with a thin waist and slightly curved lines. The color of the lacquer is red in black, which is very elegant and attractive.
Duyu zither, Lingqi style, ancient zither of the Tang Dynasty, made of tung wood, with "Duyu" engraved on the back of the dragon pond.

It is in the Zhongni style, with black lacquer on the top and bottom, a tung wood top, a screw inlay emblem, ivory quarters and wild goose feet; the yue-shan, seung-lu, dragon gums, crown horns, etc. are all made of rosewood. The name "Mingquan" is engraved in seal script under the square pool.

Zhongni style, ivory square and goose feet. It has a thin emblem of a screw. The name of the instrument is engraved below the square pond with the word "Ziqiong" in running script. The top right of the dragon pond is engraved with the following inscription: "Its quality is as straight as the Qiong tree, its color is as fine as the poor Hua, and its sound is as crisp as the Qiong rectangular and the Qiong pipe clear".

Tang Dynasty zither, Zhongni style. The body of the instrument is round and slender, and the lacquer is dark brown. Its sound is subtle and delicate, round and long. The bottom of the instrument is engraved in seal script with "Qiu Lai" and "De Zhai Collection", and the inside of the belly is inscribed with "Made by Li Jin in the third year of the Tang Dynasty".
It is black lacquer, with the word "Fengming" in regular script above the dragon pond, and a seal of "Zhonghe Qi" below the pond. The sound quality of this instrument is simple and pure.

The back of the instrument is inscribed with the word "Pine Wind" and the following inscription: "Suddenly, the end of the green apple is born with a pole, and there is no such thing as an angry trumpet.

Red and black lacquer. On the back, above the dragon pond is engraved "Lightning" in seal script, with an inscription in cursive script: "The viciousness of all things is vibrating, and the dust is falling. No delusion to fly and no breakage, is the name of the sky with".

It is a famous zither of the Song Dynasty, Zhongni style, and should be regarded as an "official zither" of the Huizong period. Inscribed in small seal script, "Golden Bell", and inscribed in official script, "Leisurely accepting evil, guiding virtue and declaring emotion."

The famous zither of the Song Dynasty, in the Zhongni style, is engraved with the inscription "The Moon in the Sea and its Clear Radiance". The inscription: "The moon in the water, the sound in the scene, the meaning in the edge. The moon in the water, the sound in the scene, the meaning in the edge. The moon in the water, the sound in the scenery, the meaning in the edge.

It is made of tung wood and engraved with the word "Feiquan" in cursive script, and also with the inscription in seal script: "The jade slippery mountain, the golden sound of the empty valley. It is a precious instrument for the most important people, and the philosophers are close to it.

It is said to have been created by the famous Wei Yang Ying, and is engraved with "Jade Linglong" in running script. The whole instrument has a thick weather, rounded dragon pond and flat rounded phoenix marsh.

On the bottom of the instrument are the four characters "Tianfeng Haitao" in seal script. The body of the instrument is made of tung wood, painted black, and the thirteen emblems are inlaid with gold pieces, and the bottom of the instrument is made of jade with two goose feet and seven quarters. There are two lines of ink writing inside the dragon pond: "Saint Song Long Xing A Shen rebuilt, the Great Tang Lei Wei pro hack.

It was a zither of the famous literary figure Sima Xiangru in the Han Dynasty. "The inscription inside the zither says: "Tongzhi is the best". When Xiangru got the "Green Qi", it was like a treasure. His mastery of the zither was matched with the wonderful sound of the instrument, which made it famous for a long time.

The maker of the Jiao-wei qin was Cai Yong, a famous Confucian scholar of the Eastern Han Dynasty. Cai Yong once came across a fire, and in the midst of the fire, he suddenly found an unusual piece of wutong wood. He risked his life and rushed into the fire to save the wood. He built it with great care and finally made a seven-stringed zither. Since the end of the wood was still burned by the fire, it was called the "scorched tail".

A famous zither of the Tang dynasty, in the Fuxi style, said to be the work of Lei of the Tang Dynasty. It is engraved in seal script with the inscription "Nine skies and the ring of pearls", and also with the inscription in running script "Amiable spring breeze and the sound of the ring of pearls".

A famous zither of the Tang Dynasty, the Shen Nong style zither. It is engraved with the cursive inscription "The Great Sage's Legacy" and also with the inscription in clerical script: "The gorge welcomes the autumn, the cold river marks the moon. The sound of the lone tung is soughing and cracking."
Zhongni style. Pine wood top and catalpa wood backing. The tone is old and bright, with the sound of gold and stone. Inscription on the back of the instrument: Yiwu Mingquan.

It is said that the music is as beautiful as heavenly music. According to legend, King Chu Chuang got the zither and loved it so much that he played it every day for seven days without going to work. When his wife Fan Ji saw this, she advised him not to lose his will by playing.

It is made of zitan wood with black lacquer and chestnut lacquer, a tung wood top, and a screw inlay emblem; the yue-shan, seung-lu, dragon gums, crown horns, quarters, and the feet are all made of zitan wood. The name of the instrument is engraved in seal script under the square pond: "Spiritual Rhythm of the Peak".
